\begin_layout Section
Rough Sketch of the Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consumers can move to a certain region with higher mobility and better income
 - and they can also stay in the same area and hope for unlikely mobility.
 We use a model to movement not for income but for mobility.
 The consumer households are thus dynasties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The utility the consumers gets is from overall maximiation of income.
 A higher income is confalted with status.
 So there are no status or positional concerns the consumers optimise.
 While consumers don't achieve status form money - but their wealth matters
 less in a poor area.
 In other words, the assets matter only with respect to a local reference.
 The consumer can therefore substitute moving to another area.
 The drop in utility by moving should still be there - since movement is
 not always possible - but the consumer also has the hope to move up because
 of local hierarchy.
\end_layout

